{{Infobox aircraft occurrence | name =1948 Sabena DC-4 Crash | image = KLM PH-TAR Douglas DC-4.jpg | caption = A KLM DC-4, similar to the accident aircraft |image_size=300 | occurrence_type =Accident | date = {{start date|1948|05|12|df=y}} | summary = Extreme weather conditions | site = 27km South of [[Libenge]] | coordinates = <!-- Following entries are for an occurrence involving a single aircraft: --> | passengers = 25 | crew = 7 | injuries =1 | fatalities = 31 | missing = | survivors = 1 | aircraft_type = [[Douglas DC-4-1009]] | aircraft_name = | Operator=[[Sabena]] | tail_number = OO-CBE | Origin= [[Léopoldville-N'Djili Airport]] (FIH/FZAA), [[Congo Democratic Republic|Congo]] (Democratic Republic) | stopover = | stopover0 = | stopover1 = | stopover2 = | stopover3 = | stopover4 = | stopover5 = | last_stopover = | Destination= [[Libenge Airport]] (LIE/FZFA), [[Congo Democratic Republic|Congo]] (Democratic Republic) }}
The '''1948 Sabena DC-4 Crash''' was the crash of a [[Douglas DC-4-1009]] of the Belgian airline [[Sabena]], 27&nbsp;km South of [[Libenge]], [[Congo Democratic Republic|Congo]] (Democratic Republic) on 12 May 1948. It was the deadliest accident for [[Sabena]] at the time and the second of three deadly [[Sabena]] crashes in 1948. It was also the deadliest in Belgian [[Congo Democratic Republic|Congo]] before the country's independence in 1960, of the 32 people on board 31 were killed, leaving only 1 survivor.<ref name=ESM>{{cite book|title=Rampen in België|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dly9axBP4O4C&pg=PA67|year=2005|publisher=Lannoo Uitgeverij|isbn=978-90-209-6216-1|page=67}}</ref>
==Aircraft== The DC-4-1009 involved was built in 1946 and bought new from Douglas with serial number 42932 and registration ''OO-CBE'' and was used by the [[Belgium|Belgian]] airline company [[Sabena]] from 17 April 1946 until its destruction in 1948.<ref name=NFR>{{cite web |url=https://www.planelogger.com/Aircraft/View?Registration=OO-CBE&DeliveryDate=08.04.46 |title=Registration Details For OO-CBE (Sabena) DC-4-1009 |publisher=planelogger.com |date=2015 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> The aircraft was mostly used in Belgian Congo and carried Regent [[Prince Charles of Belgium]] back to [[Belgium]] on 13 August 1947 after his official visit to Congo.<ref name=WSM>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbap.be/archivalia/sabena/picturessab2.htm |title=Sabena part 2 |publisher=sbap.be |date=2014 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>
== Crash == The Sabena flight departed from [[Léopoldville-N'Djili Airport]], [[Congo Democratic Republic]] en route to [[Libenge Airport]], [[Congo Democratic Republic]] with 25 passengers and 7 crew members on board.<ref name=VSM>{{cite web |url=http://www.planecrashinfo.com/1948/1948-31.htm |title=OO-CBE |publisher=planecrashinfo.com |date= |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>
==Probable cause== While above the Congo [[rainforest]], 27&nbsp;km South of [[Libenge]], at an altitude of 700 feet, the aircraft probably penetrated a very turbulent line of clouds or flew the aircraft into the active centre of a tornado at a low altitude. The aircraft was probably then forced to the ground by a down-ward gust.,<ref name=GSM/>
The aircraft hit the tree-tops and left a {{convert|200|m|abbr=on}} trail through the forest until it finally crashed, killing all 7 crew members and 24 of the 25 passengers,<ref name=GSM>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19480512-0 |title=Accident description |publisher=aviation-safety.net |date=1996 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> the sole survivor was an [[Egypt]]ian man named Moutafis.
==Aftermath== The wreck was located the following day and the injured sole survivor was rescued. Rescuers searched for more survivors, but it quickly became clear that their efforts were in vain. This crash was the second deadly crash of three involving a [[Sabena]] aircraft in 1948, making 1948 the deadliest year in Sabena's history.<ref name=NAM>{{cite web |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1948/05/16/page/2/article/only-one-survivor-believed-on-plane-in-belgian-congo-crash |title=Only one survivor believed on plane in Belgian Congo crash |publisher=chicago Tribune |date=15 May 1948 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>
